Here's a simple Discord bot with a single `ban` command using Discord.js v14. Make sure you have a bot token ready by creating a bot on the Discord Developer Portal and getting the token from there.
```javascript
const { Client, Intents, Collection } = require('discord.js');
const { SlashCommandBuilder } = require('@discordjs/builders');

const clientId = 'YOUR_CLIENT_ID';
const guildId = 'YOUR_GUILD_ID';
const token = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN';

const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.Guilds, Intents.FLAGS.GuildMembers, Intents.FLAGS.GuildBans] });

client.once('ready', async () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const { commandName, options } = interaction;

  if (commandName === 'ban') {
    const member = interaction.guild.members.cache.get(options.get('member').value);
    if (!member) return interaction.reply('Member not found!');

    const reason = options.getString('reason');
    if (!reason) return interaction.reply('Please provide a reason for the ban.');

    const bans = interaction.guild.bans.cache;
    if (bans.has(member.user.id)) return interaction.reply(`${member.user.tag} is already banned.`);

    await member.ban({ reason: reason });
    interaction.reply(`${member.user.tag} has been banned.`);
  }
});

client.login(token);
```
This code creates a simple bot that listens for the `/ban` slash command. When the command is executed, it checks if the specified member is in the server, and if they are, it checks if the member is already banned or not. If the member is not already banned, the bot bans the member with the provided reason and sends a message to the user who executed the command.

Make sure to replace `YOUR_CLIENT_ID`, `YOUR_GUILD_ID`, and `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your actual client ID, guild ID, and bot token respectively.

In this example, we'll create a Dockerfile to set up a testing environment using Cypress, and then write a testing framework that captures screenshots and saves them.

1. Create a new directory for your project and navigate into it:
```bash
mkdir cypress-testing-framework
cd cypress-testing-framework
```

2. Create a `Dockerfile` in the project directory:
```Dockerfile
# Use an official Node.js image as the base image
FROM node:14.17.0-alpine3.12

# Set the working directory to /app
WORKDIR /app

# Copy package.json into the container
COPY package*.json./

# Install node_modules
RUN npm install

# Copy the rest of the application into the container
COPY..

# Expose port 3000
EXPOSE 3000

# Start the application
CMD ["npm", "start"]
```

3. Create a `package.json` file in the project directory:
```json
{
  "name": "cypress-testing-framework",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "index.js",
  "scripts": {
    "test": "cypress open --config baseUrl=http://localhost:3000",
    "start": "node index.js"
  },
  "dependencies": {
    "cypress": "^9.2.2"
  }
}
```

4. Create an `index.js` file in the project directory:
```javascript
const Cypress = require('cypress');

(async () => {
  try {
    // Start the Cypress server
    await Cypress.Server.start({
      project: './cypress',
    });

    // Create a server to serve your application
    const server = require('./server.js');
    server.listen(3000, () => {
      console.log('Server listening on port 3000');
    });
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
})();
```

5. Create a `server.js` file in the project directory:
```javascript
const http = require('http');
const app = require('./app.js');

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;

const server = http.createServer(app);

server.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server is listening on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

6. Create an `app.js` file in the project directory:
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello World!');
});

module.exports = app;
```

7. Create a `cypress` directory in the project directory and initialize Cypress in it:
```bash
mkdir cypress
cd cypress
npx cypress open --config baseUrl=http://localhost:3000
```
This will open the Cypress test runner, where you can write your tests.

8. Inside the `cypress` directory, create a new test file, for example, `myFirstTest.spec.js`:
```javascript
describe('My First Test', () => {
  it('Visits the homepage and takes a screenshot', () => {
    cy.visit('/');
    cy.get('h1').should('contain', 'Hello World!');
    cy.screenshot();
  });
});
```

9. Run your Docker container:
```bash
docker-compose up --build
```

This will start a Docker container with Node.js, Cypress, and your application. The Cypress test runner will be available at `http://localhost:9000`.

Now you have a testing framework in Cypress that utilizes Docker and captures screenshots and saves them. You can extend this framework and write more tests as needed.

